{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c18f39e2-1285-4bd1-9234-5db681135b82","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**Issue 1 — `&&` with `dynamic` and interface operators**\n\nC# 15 tightened compile-time validation of short-circuit operators (`&&`/`||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the entire expression was deferred to the DLR at runtime. Now the compiler statically checks the non-dynamic operand's type for **all three** required pieces: `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`.\n\n`IFilter` defines `true`/`false` but **no `operator &`**, so the compiler rejects `left && right` at compile time.\n\n**Fixes** (pick one):\n```csharp\n// Option A: Add operator & to the interface\ninterface IFilter\n{\n    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;\n    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;\n    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;\n}\n\n// Option B: Cast to the concrete type that has all three operators\nvar combined = (CompositeFilter)left && right;\n\n// Option C: Decompose the short-circuit manually\nvar combined = IFilter.op_True(left) ? left : IFilter.op_False(left) ? /*...*/ : right;\n```\n\n---\n\n**Issue 2 — `ref readonly` lambda return → CS0518**\n\nCS0518 (\"predefined type not defined or imported\") means the compiler recognizes the `ref readonly` return lambda syntax (new/changed in C# 15) but cannot find a required well-known BCL type to represent it. This is almost always a **SDK ↔ target framework mismatch** — you have the C# 15 compiler but your `TargetFramework` isn't `net11.0`.\n\n**Fixes** (pick one):\n```xml\n<!-- Option A: Ensure your TFM matches the compiler -->\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n```csharp\n// Option B: Use an explicit delegate type (works on older TFMs)\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\nRefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n\n// Option C: Use a local function instead of a lambda\nstatic ref readonly int Fn() => ref value;\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5357a3d0-6a0d-4269-9b05-9e18c7c3afa7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both issues from my knowledge of C# language evolution.\n\n**Issue 1: `left && right` with `dynamic` and user-defined operators**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler resolves short-circuiting operators (`&&` and `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe `&&` operator in C# is synthesized from `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler historically deferred resolution entirely to runtime. \n\nBut C# 15 changed how this interaction works, particularly with static operators defined on interfaces. The interface here defines static `operator true` and `operator false` methods, and when the compiler tries to resolve the `&&` operation with a `dynamic` operand against a type implementing that interface, it's now stricter about which operators it can use at compile time versus deferring to runtime. The real issue is that C# 14/15 tightened how the compiler handles `&&` and `||` with `dynamic` operands—it now requires the static type to have both the short-circuit operators (`true`/`false`) AND the bitwise operators (`&`/`|`), rather than deferring everything to the runtime binder. So the fix is either adding `operator &` to `IFilter` or casting to a concrete type that has all the required operators.\n\nFor the second issue with `ref readonly` lambda returns, the CS0518 error suggests the compiler is trying to synthesize a delegate type to represent the lambda's signature, but the necessary runtime support or attribute isn't available in the target framework. For Issue 2, C# 15 likely introduced new parsing for `ref readonly` return lambdas, recognizing syntax like `ref readonly int () => ref value` as valid. The problem is the compiler now expects a corresponding predefined delegate type (possibly something like `RefReadOnlyReturningFunc<T>`) to exist in the BCL to represent this construct, but it hasn't been defined yet or isn't available in the current framework.\n\nFor Issue 1, I'm suspecting this is a breaking change in how the compiler handles the `&&` operator when used with interface types and dynamic expressions.  In C# 15, the compiler likely became stricter about validating that the static type has the complete short-circuit operator pattern—`operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`—before allowing `dynamic` to participate. Since `IFilter` only defines `true` and `false` but not `&`, the compiler now rejects it rather than deferring to runtime resolution.\n\nFor Issue 2, the CS0518 error suggests the compiler is looking for a predefined delegate type that should exist for `ref readonly` return values, but either it's missing or the inference logic for lambda natural types changed in C# 15 in a way that breaks this pattern. For the second issue, I need to make sure the target framework is set to `net11.0` and matches the SDK version, or switch to an explicit delegate type or local function instead of relying on the lambda syntax.","outputTokens":3047},"id":"1654081e-fa9e-4b5c-8ae8-ef60a5dadca7","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:07:40.010Z","parentId":"8692a2bd-aebb-4d2f-93d0-55dd21bd38fd"}
